# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: backdraft
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:backdraft/1408-film] The film follows Mike Enslin, an author who investigates allegedly haunted places.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Enslin receives an ominous warning not to enter room 1408 at a New York City hotel, The Dolphin.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Although skeptical of the paranormal, he is soon trapped in the room, where he experiences bizarre and frightful events.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Mike Enslin is a cynical and skeptical author of niche books about supernatural events, in which he has no belief.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] While promoting his latest book in Hermosa Beach, California, he receives an anonymous postcard depicting The Dolphin, a hotel on Lexington Avenue in New York City, bearing the message: "Don't enter 1408." Viewing this as a challenge, Mike travels to The Dolphin and requests room 1408.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] The hotel manager, Gerald Olin, attempts to discourage him.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] He explains to Mike that in the last 95 years, no one has lasted more than an hour inside of 1408; the latest count is 56 deaths.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Olin repeatedly and impassionately attempts to dissuade and bribe Mike, but at Mike's insistence and threat of legal action against the hotel, preparations are reluctantly made.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] While Mike describes the room's ordinary appearance and absence of supernatural behavior on his mini-cassette recorder as the "banality of evil", the clock radio suddenly starts playing The Carpenters' "We've Only Just Begun", and the digital display changes to a countdown starting from 60:00.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Mike begins to see ghosts of the room's past victims, along with flashbacks of his deceased daughter Katie and his terminally ill father.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Mike makes numerous attempts to leave the room, all in vain.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Mike uses his laptop to contact his estranged wife Lily and ask for help.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] The room activates the sprinkler system, short-circuiting the laptop, which starts to work again when the temperature drops to subzero.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] A doppelgänger of Mike appears in a video chat window, urging Lily to come to the hotel room.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] The room starts to shake violently, causing Mike to crash into a picture of a ship in a storm, from which water floods the room.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] He finds himself reliving a surfing accident from before he entered the room.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Recovering in the hospital, he reconciles with Lily and assumes his experience in 1408 was just a nightmare; Lily encourages him to write a book about it.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] When visiting the post office to send the manuscript to his publisher, he recognizes members of a construction crew as Dolphin Hotel staff, who start destroying the walls, revealing that Mike is still trapped inside 1408.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Katie's ghost confronts him, and when the countdown ends, the room restores itself and the clock radio resets to 60:00.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] A female voice calling herself "hotel operator" calls Mike.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Mike asks why he has not been killed yet and she informs him that guests enjoy free will: he can relive the past hour over and over again, or use their "express checkout system".
[src:backdraft/1408-film] A hangman's noose appears, but he refuses to give in.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] The voices call once again, threatening that even if he escapes, he will never leave.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Mike tells them to not send his wife to the room, hanging up as the phone begins to melt.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Mike improvises a Molotov cocktail and sets the room on fire.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] He then lies down and laughs in victory upon destroying the room.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] The hotel is evacuated and Olin, in his office, praises Mike for his actions.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Mike is rescued from the room by firefighters and he reconciles with Lily, though she is skeptical of his experience.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] She finds a box of Mike's possessions that were rescued from 1408 and Mike takes the damaged mini-cassette recorder from it, saying: "Sometimes you can't get rid of bad memories.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] You've just got to live with them." Mike briefly tampers with the recorder, making it work again.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Suddenly, they both hear Katie's voice coming from it, confirming Mike's account.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] In November 2003 and 2004, Dimension Films optioned the rights to the 1999 short story "1408" by Stephen King.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] The studio hired Matt Greenberg to adapt the story into a screenplay.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] In October 2005, Mikael Håfström was hired to direct, with the screenplay being rewritten by Scott Alexander and Larry Karaszewski.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] In March 2006, John Cusack was cast to star in the film, joined by Samuel L.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] In July, Kate Walsh was cast to star opposite Cusack as the protagonist's ex-wife, but she was forced to exit in August due to scheduling conflicts with her role on *Grey's Anatomy*.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] According to Cusack, the Roosevelt Hotel in New York was used for some of the exterior shots of the Dolphin.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] The lobby scenes were filmed at the Reform Club in London.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] There are four endings that were shot for the film.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] In addition to the ending that appears in the theatrical release, three other alternative endings were shot.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] In 2007, it was reported that director Mikael Håfström said the ending of the film was reshot because test audiences felt that the original was a "downer".
[src:backdraft/1408-film] However, in a 2024 interview, Håfström clarified that the theatrical ending was shot first and that alternate endings were later shot in a desire to "experiment".
[src:backdraft/1408-film] He also stated that he feels that the theatrical ending is "more rewarding" and "stronger, and much more emotional".
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Mike dies in the fire, but is happy to see the room destroyed.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] He spitefully laughs as the room screams in agony, and everything burns and crashes on top of him.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] At Mike's funeral, Olin approaches Lily and Mike's publisher Sam Farrell.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] He unsuccessfully attempts to give her a box of Mike's possessions, including the tape recorder.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Olin states that Mike did not die in vain, as the room was successfully destroyed.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] He later listens to the recording in his car and is saddened when he hears Katie's voice on the tape.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] He sees a little girl in a dress walking on the cemetery grass behind the car, calling out as if she is lost.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] He then sees Mike's burnt corpse in the backseat.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Then he sees the same girl holding hands with her father as they walk away.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Olin places the tape recorder back in the box and drives off.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] The final scene is of the gutted room, where an apparition of Mike assesses the death of the entity while smoking a cigarette.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] He hears his daughter calling for him and disappears as he walks toward the door.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] A door is heard closing and the scene fades.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Instead of the funeral scene, the sounds of a funeral are dubbed over shots of Los Angeles.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Lily and Sam sort through Mike's effects.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Sam returns to his New York office and discovers the manuscript that Mike wrote while he was in room 1408.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] As Sam reads the story, audio from Mike's experiences in the room is heard.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] In a final scene, Sam's office doors slam shut and Mike's father's voice says: "As you are, I was.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] An alternative version of the theatrical ending, it has the same events but Lily does not acknowledge hearing Katie's voice on the tape and Mike reacts very happily at hearing her voice on the tape.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] The DVD was released on October 2, 2007, by Genius Products with a standard 1-Disc Edition containing only the theatrical cut and a 2-Disc Collector's Edition that contained both the theatrical and director's cut.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] On September 16, 2008, Genius released the movie on Blu-ray containing the director's cut.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] For many years, the theatrical cut remained elusive, as streaming platforms and several television broadcasts only had the director's cut.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] However, in 2021, when Lionsgate acquired the Weinstein Company library (which included everything Dimension Films released post-2005), they released the theatrical cut onto streaming platforms for the first time.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Lionsgate released the film containing both cuts onto Ultra HD Blu-ray on January 13, 2026, marking the first time since the initial 2007 DVD release that the theatrical cut has gotten a domestic physical home video release.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] In its opening weekend, *1408* opened in second place at the box office, grossing US$20.6 million in 2,678 theaters.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] *1408* had a production budget of US$25 million.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] The film went on to gross US$132 million, of which US$71.9 million was from Canada and the United States.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Audiences polled by CinemaScore gave the film an average grade of "B−" on an A+ to F scale.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] James Berardinelli awarded the film three out of four, calling it "the best horror film of the year".
[src:backdraft/1408-film] He offered significant praise for Cusack's performance as Mike Enslin, writing: "This is John Cusack's movie to carry, and he has no problem taking it where it needs to go." He found the film "reminds us what it's like to be scared in a theater rather than overwhelmed by buckets of blood and gore".
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Some critics called the film far superior to other adaptations of Stephen King novels and stories.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Mick LaSalle of the *San Francisco Chronicle* described it as "one of the good Stephen King adaptations, one that maintains its author's sly sense of humor and satiric view of human nature" and "more genuinely scary movie than most horror films".
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Several critics found the film underwhelming.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Wesley Morris of *The Boston Globe* wrote a mixed review, describing the film as "a lot of consonants and no vowels".
[src:backdraft/1408-film] He compared it unfavorably to *The Shining*, a similar King adaptation, believing *1408* lacked that film's "lunging horror and dramatic architecture".
[src:backdraft/1408-film] He wrote that it "conjures a wonderful anticipatory mood of dread in the first 30 minutes, then blows it to stylish smithereens".
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Rob Salem of the *Toronto Star* gave the film two out of four for seeming a predictable "hit and miss" production.
[src:backdraft/1408-film] Like Morris, Salem wrote: "Even as haunted hotel King movies go, *1408* is certainly no *Shining*.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:backdraft/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The idea of fighting forest fires from the air dates back at least as far as Friedrich Karl von Koenig-Warthausen's observations on seeing a blaze when overflying the Santa Lucia Range, California, in 1929.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] A wide variety of terminology has been used in the popular media for the aircraft (and methods) used in aerial firefighting.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The terms **airtanker** or **air tanker** generally refer to fixed-wing aircraft based in the United States; "airtanker" is used in official documentation.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The term "**waterbomber**" is used in some Canadian government documents for the same class of vehicles, though it sometimes has a connotation of amphibians.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] A wide variety of helicopters and fixed-wing aircraft are used for aerial firefighting.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Forest Service and Bureau of Land Management own, lease, or contract for nearly 1,000 aircraft each fire season, with annual expenditures in excess of US$250 million in recent years".
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Helicopters may be fitted with tanks (helitankers) or they may carry buckets.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Some helitankers, such as the Erickson AirCrane, are also outfitted with a front-mounted foam cannon.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Buckets are usually filled by submerging or dipping them in lakes, rivers, reservoirs, or portable tanks.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The most popular of the buckets is the flexible Bambi Bucket.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Tanks can be filled on the ground (by water tenders or truck-mounted systems) or water can be siphoned from lakes, rivers, reservoirs, or a portable tank through a hanging snorkel.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Currently the world's largest helicopter, the Mil Mi-26, uses a Bambi bucket.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The Mendocino Air Tanker Squad formed by Joseph Bolles Ely in 1956 was the first such unit in the United States to drop water and retardant on fires.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Based at the Willows-Glenn County Airport it soon led the way for other agencies to form similar squads.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Though World War II- and Korean War-era bombers were for a long time the mainstay of the aerial firefighting fleet, newer purpose-built tankers have since come online.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The smallest are the Single Engine Air Tankers (SEATs).
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] These are agricultural sprayers that generally drop about 800 US gallons (3,000 L) of water or retardant.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Examples include the Air Tractor AT-802, which can deliver around 800 gallons of water or fire retardant solution in each drop, and the Soviet Antonov An-2 biplane.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Both of these aircraft can be fitted with floats that scoop water from the surface of a body of water.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Similar in configuration to the World War II–era Consolidated PBY Catalina, the Canadair CL-215 and its derivative the CL-415 are designed and built specifically for firefighting.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The Croatian Air Force uses six CL-415s as well as six AT 802s for firefighting purposes.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Conair also converted a number of Convair 580 and Fokker F27 Friendship turboprop airliners to air tankers.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The largest aerial firefighter ever used is a Boeing 747 aerial firefighter, known as the Global Supertanker, that can carry 19,600 US gallons (74,200 L) fed by a pressurized drop system.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The Supertanker was deployed operationally for the first time in 2009, fighting a fire in Spain.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The tanker made its first American operation on August 31, 2009, at the Oak Glen Fire.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] It has since been replaced by a Boeing 747-400.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Another wide body jetliner that is currently being used as an air tanker is the modified McDonnell Douglas DC-10-30 operated by the 10 Tanker Air Carrier company as the DC-10 Air Tanker.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] It can carry up to 12,000 US gallons (45,400 L) of fire fighting retardant.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The Russian Ministry of Emergency Situations operates convertible-to-cargo Ilyushin Il-76 airtankers that have been operating with 11,000-US-gallon (41,600 L) tanking systems, and several Beriev Be-200 jet powered amphibian aircraft.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The Be-200 can carry a maximum payload of about 12,000 litres (3,200 US gal) of water, making "scoops" in suitable stretches of water in 14 seconds.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Bombardier's Dash 8 Q Series aircraft are the basis of new, next-generation air tankers.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Cascade Aerospace has converted two pre-owned Q400s to act as part-time water bomber and part-time transport aircraft for France's Sécurité Civile, while Neptune Aviation is converting a pre-owned Q300 as a prototype to augment its Lockheed P-2 Neptune aircraft.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The Sécurité Civile also operates twelve Canadair CL-415 and nine Conair Turbo Firecat aircraft.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Neptune Aviation also currently operates converted British Aerospace 146 jetliners as air tankers.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The BAe 146 can carry up to 3,000 gallons of fire fighting retardant.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Air Spray USA Ltd. of Chico, California has also converted the BAe 146 jetliner to the role of air tanker.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Another modern-era passenger aircraft that has now been converted for aerial firefighting missions in the U.S. is the McDonnell Douglas MD-87 jetliner operated by Erickson Aero Tanker.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The MD-87 can carry up to 4,000 gallons of fire fighting retardant.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Coulson Aviation unveiled a Boeing 737-300 firefighting conversion in May 2017.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Six aircraft have been purchased from Southwest Airlines for the RADS system conversion which was planned to enter service in December 2017.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The 737 aircraft is smaller than the C-130Q which allows for a wider range of airfields to be utilized.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Britt Coulson further stated the aircraft will be able to retain the current seat and galley configuration for tanker operations.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] On 22 November 2018, the 737 was used for the first time to fight a fire near Newcastle, Australia.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] In July 2022, Airbus tested the aerial firefighting capacity of the A400M using a roll-on/roll-off kit comprising a 20-tonne water tank and piping allowing the load to be expelled from the end of the cargo ramp.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] All links, citations and data sources are listed in the paragraph above.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] For accident and grounding citations, see paragraph below table.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Other former military aircraft utilized as firefighting air tankers in the U.S. in the past included the B-17 and the PB4Y-2, a version of the B-24.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The Lead Plane function directs the activities of the airtankers by both verbal target descriptions and by physically leading the airtankers on the drop run.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The leadplane is typically referred to as a "Bird Dog" in Canada or "Supervision" aircraft in Australia.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The O-2 Skymaster, Cessna 310 and OV-10 Bronco have been used as spotter and lead plane platforms.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources has also used the Cessna 337.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The Beechcraft Baron was long used as a leadplane or air attack ship, but most were retired in 2003; more common now is the Beechcraft King Air and the Twin Commander 690.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] A Cessna Citation 500 jet owned by Air Spray (1967) LTd. was used by the British Columbia Ministry of Forests beginning in 1995 and used for two fire seasons to lead the very fast Electra L188 air tanker to the fires.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] This was the first time a jet aircraft was used as a lead plane or "bird dog".
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The Department of Parks and Wildlife in Western Australia operates a fleet of nine American Champion Scouts 8GCBC during the summer months as spotter aircraft and Air Attack platforms.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The Provinces of Alberta and British Columbia and the Yukon Territories contract to supply Twin Commander 690 as bird dog aircraft for their air tanker fleets.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Air Spray owns 9 Twin Commander 690 for use as bird dog aircraft.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] In the United States, most of these aircraft are privately owned and contracted to government agencies, and the National Guard and the U.S.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Marines also maintain fleets of firefighting aircraft.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Forest Service (USFS) and the Bureau of Land Management (BLM) announced that they were cancelling contracts with operators of 33 heavy airtankers.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] They cited liability concerns and an inability to safely manage the fleet after the wing failure and resulting crash of a C-130A Hercules in California and a PB4Y-2 in Colorado during the summer of 2002.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Both aged aircraft broke up in flight due to catastrophic fatigue cracks at the wing roots.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] After subsequent third-party examination and extensive testing of all USFS contracted heavy airtankers, three companies were awarded contracts and now maintain a combined fleet of 23 aircraft.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Borate salts used in the past to fight wildfires have been found to sterilize the soil and be toxic to animals so are now prohibited.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Newer retardants use ammonium sulfate or ammonium polyphosphate with attapulgite clay thickener or diammonium phosphate with a guar gum derivative thickener.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Fire retardants often contain wetting agents, preservatives and rust inhibitors and are colored red with ferric oxide or fugitive color to mark where they have been dropped.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Brand names of fire retardants for aerial application include Fortress and Phos-Chek.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Some water-dropping aircraft carry tanks of a guar gum derivative to thicken the water and reduce runoff.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Helicopters can hover over the fire and drop water or retardant.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The S-64 Helitanker has microprocessor-controlled doors on its tank.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] The doors are controlled based on the area to be covered and wind conditions.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Fixed-wing aircraft must make a pass and drop water or retardant like a bomber.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Water is not usually dropped directly on flames because its effect is short-lived.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Fire retardants are not typically used to extinguish the fire, but instead are used to contain the fire, or slow it down to allow ground crews to contain it.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Because of this, retardants are usually dropped in front of or around a moving fire, rather than directly on it, creating a firebreak.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Aerial firefighting is most effectively used in conjunction with ground-based efforts, as aircraft are only one weapon in the firefighting arsenal.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] However, there have been cases of aircraft extinguishing fires long before ground crews were able to reach them.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] Some firefighting aircraft can refill their tanks in mid-flight, by flying down to skim the surface of large bodies of water.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] This is particularly useful in rural areas where flying back to an airbase for refills may take too much time.
[src:backdraft/aerial-firefighting] In 2002 an Ontario CL-415 crew was able to refill 100 times within a 4-hour mission, delivering 162,000 US gallons (613,240 L) or 1,350,000 pounds (612 t) of water on a fire near Dryden, Ontario (June 1, 2002 Dryden fire # 10 Tanker #271 civil ident C-GOGE).
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Airports with scheduled passenger flights are obliged to have firefighters and firefighting apparatus on location ready for duty any time aircraft operate.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Airports may have regulatory oversight by an arm of their individual national governments or voluntarily under standards of the International Civil Aviation Organization.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Due to the mass casualty potential of an aviation emergency, the speed with which emergency response equipment and personnel arrive at the scene of the emergency is of paramount importance.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Their arrival and initial mission to secure the aircraft against all hazards, particularly fire, increases the survivability of the passengers and crew on board.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Airport firefighters have advanced training in the application of firefighting foams, dry chemical and clean agents used to extinguish burning aviation fuel in and around an aircraft in order to maintain a path for evacuating passengers to exit the fire hazard area.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Further, should fire either be encountered in the cabin or extend there from an external fire, the ARFF responders must work to control/extinguish these fires as well.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Primary to the hazard mitigation and safe evacuation of ambulatory passengers is the need to perform rescue operations.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Passengers unable to extricate themselves must be removed from the aircraft and provided medical care.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] This process is extremely labor-intensive, requiring both firefighters and support personnel.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Due to the nature of a mass casualty incident, rescue workers employ triage to classify the victims and direct their efforts where they can maximize survival.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Subsequent to the emergency being declared under control, the ARFF function reverts to one of protecting the scene, eliminating any peripheral or slowly evolving hazards and assisting to preserve the scene for investigators.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] In 2016, an Emirati fire fighter died from burns when trying to fight the fire in the Emirates Flight 521 crash.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Due to the rarity of aircraft fires, firefighters often have other usual duties such as luggage loaders or security guards, which they have to abandon at fire alarms.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Specialized fire apparatus are required for the ARFF function, the design of which is predicated on many factors but primarily: speed, water-carrying capacity, off-road performance, and agent discharge rates.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Since an accident could occur anywhere on or off airport property, sufficient water and other agents must be carried to contain the fire to allow for the best possibility of extinguishment, maximum possibility for evacuation and/or until additional resources arrive on the scene.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] They also must wear self-contained breathing apparatus to provide a source of clean air, enabling them to work in the presence of smoke or other super-heated gases, such as when making entry into the burning cabin of an aircraft.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) mandates ARFF operations at all U.S. airports that serve scheduled passenger air carriers.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] These are the only civilian fire protection services that are specifically regulated by any governmental entity.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Military bases may have their own ARFF services with specialized duties and training.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Airports required to have ARFF services are inspected at least annually by the FAA for compliance with FAR, Part 139.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Military ARFF operations must meet the mission requirements for their individual branch of the service.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] In many cases the FAA will perform the investigatory duties after an incident, but in instances where significant injuries or any fatal accident the National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) will investigate and the ARFF contingent will assist where needed.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] An index is assigned to each FAA Part 139 certificate holder based on a combination of the air carrier aircraft length and the average number of daily departures.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] If the longest air carrier aircraft at the airport has five or more average daily departures, the matching index is used.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] If the longest aircraft has less than five average daily departures, the next lower index is used.
[src:backdraft/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] That index determines the required number of ARFF vehicles and required amount of extinguishing agents.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] An **airport crash tender** (known in some countries as an **airport fire appliance**) is a specialised fire engine designed for use in aircraft firefighting at aerodromes, airports, and military air bases.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] They can be mounted on 4x4, 6x6, or even 8x8 wheeled chassis.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] In order to decrease their turning radius, all four of the 8x8 wheeled unit's front wheels may be steerable.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] Newer airport crash tenders also incorporate twin-agent nozzles/injection systems to inject a stream of Purple-K dry chemical into the AFFF firefighting foam stream, helping to extinguish the fire faster.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] Some also have Halotron tanks with handlines for situations that require a clean agent to be utilized.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] These features allow airport crash tenders to reach an aircraft quickly, and rapidly put out large fires with jet fuel involved.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] Some tenders have an elevated extended extinguishing arm capable of raising a water/foam cannon up to about 10–20 m (33–66 ft).
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] Some can then puncture superficial structures of an aeroplane to fight a fire inside the fuselage.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] The International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) has given standards and recommended practices on rescue fire fighting categories of civil aerodromes.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] National aviation authorities may have given even further requirements on aerodrome rescue and fire services.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] The rescue fire services are based on a critical aircraft size based on a statistical analysis of movements (take-offs and landings) on the airport.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] There are also minimum category levels based on e.g. the number of seats in the critical aircraft.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] Depending on the airport category, the standards determine the minimum number of rescue fire-fighting vehicles.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] In addition, requirements are given on the water and foam capacities, discharge rates for foam solutions, and minimum dry chemical powder (complementary agent) amounts, reserve stocks of fire fighting agents, ability to operate on rough terrain, and acceleration of the air crash tenders.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] The end of each runway has to be reached in a response time of two minutes or less, and any part of the movement area has to be achieved in a response time not exceeding three minutes.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] Airport rescue and firefighting services operate many specialist vehicles to provide emergency cover at airports.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] Domestic appliances are similar in function and appearance to fire appliances operated by local fire services.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] They are not as large or as heavy as airport crash tenders.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] The units are ordinarily used to respond to fire incidents in airport terminal buildings but also respond to aircraft incidents.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] The appliances carry breathing apparatus, rescue equipment, firefighting media, ladders, cutting equipment, etc.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] "*First attack*" or "*rapid intervention vehicles*" (RIV).
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] RIVs are normally smaller, nimble fire appliances capable of quick acceleration and high speed.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] They carry less equipment than domestic appliances and crash tenders but arrive first on scene at aircraft incidents to begin rescue and firefighting operations whilst heavier and larger units approach.
[src:backdraft/airport-crash-tender] *General purpose vehicles* (such as a fire chief's car or general purpose or incident support vehicles).
[src:backdraft/area-of-refuge] An **area of refuge** or **safe room** is a place in a building designed to hold occupants during a fire or other emergency when evacuation may not be safe or possible.
[src:backdraft/area-of-refuge] Occupants can wait there until rescued or relieved by firefighters.
[src:backdraft/area-of-refuge] In some instances, an area of refuge or refuge area may refer to a designated space in a multi-unit residential building that can provide relief from unsafe or uncomfortable conditions in individual units.
[src:backdraft/area-of-refuge] An area of refuge is typically supplied with a steady supply of fresh or filtered outside air.
[src:backdraft/area-of-refuge] A two way communication system is provided on each floor above or below the main floor.
[src:backdraft/area-of-refuge] A call box is required in each area of refuge, which can call into a central location called a base station.
[src:backdraft/area-of-refuge] If the station is not attended 24 hours a day, the call must automatically call to an outside location and have two-way voice person to person communication capabilities.
[src:backdraft/area-of-refuge] Such locations are usually required to be bounded by fire-resistant walls and floors.
[src:backdraft/area-of-refuge] In the context of climate change, where older buildings may not be designed for changing climate conditions, refuge spaces are sometimes discussed in terms of providing communal areas in multi-unit buildings for when temperature and air quality is not safe or comfortable in individual units.
[src:backdraft/arson] Arson is considered distinct from pyromania, an impulse control disorder characterized by an obsession with fire.
[src:backdraft/arson] Most acts of arson are not committed by pyromaniacs.
[src:backdraft/arson] Reckless burning is legally distinct from arson in some jurisdictions, but generally refers to cases where an individual causes a fire which results in death, destruction of property, or injury, through negligence or inattention.
[src:backdraft/arson] Arsonists may set fires during riots, civil unrest, ethnic cleansing or war.
[src:backdraft/arson] An arsonist may commit the crime as an act of war, terrorism, for financial gain (i.e., insurance fraud or arson-for-profit), emotional satisfaction (i.e., firefighter arson, personal entertainment, retribution, or revenge), or in the concealment of another crime like robbery or homicide.
[src:backdraft/arson] Fires are generally set using an accelerant (such as gasoline or kerosene) to ignite, propel, and direct the flames.
[src:backdraft/arson] The detection and identification of ignitable liquid residues is an important part of fire investigations.
[src:backdraft/arson] "burning"; and Edward Coke has indictment of *burning* (1640).
[src:backdraft/arson] Arson has been a documented practice for centuries.
[src:backdraft/arson] Arson (sometime called "fire setting" in scholarly literature) may have varying motivations, and can be difficult to profile.
[src:backdraft/arson] Arson may be committed for a number of reasons.
[src:backdraft/arson] The wide variety of these motivations, along with limitations on cohort size, and variations in the scholarly, legal, social, and psychological definitions of arson/fire setting makes generalizations difficult.
[src:backdraft/arson] One or more individuals may commit arson during a riot as an act of vandalism, or during civil disorder or an ethnic cleansing as an act of war, terrorism or act of political protest.
[src:backdraft/arson] For instance, it is not uncommon for buildings, cars, dumpsters to be set on fire following sporting events in some cities and nations.
[src:backdraft/arson] Fires may be set to provide "cover" to retreating or advancing forces, like in 1991 when the Iraqi military retreated from Kuwait.
[src:backdraft/arson] Groups including the Provisional IRA and the Women's Social and Political Union have used arson as a political act of violence.
[src:backdraft/arson] During the most recent Myanmar civil war the Military junta engaged in a campaign of burning homes to drive out combatants in urban areas.
[src:backdraft/arson] Inversely, arson (or intent to commit arson) has been used a false flag or smear campaign against activists, as in the case of Marinus van der Lubbe and Martin Sostre.
[src:backdraft/arson] Other motivations include financial gain (i.e., a person destroys their own property by burning it and attempts to collect against their insurance policy).
[src:backdraft/arson] In 2019 the California Department of Insurance and San Jose Fire Department were tipped off as to an insurance fraud scheme when the location of a planned incident was given to a tip line.
[src:backdraft/arson] After an investigation, a married couple and four co-conspirators were arrested and convicted with arson and insurance fraud after a string of home, business, and warehouse fires which took place over four years.
[src:backdraft/arson] The criminals left chicken in turned-on deep fryers to make the damage look like the result of a cooking accident.
[src:backdraft/arson] The group then filled insurance claims for the cost of the building, as well as smoke-damaged goods to claim fire damages for insurance payouts.
[src:backdraft/arson] The group's scheme claimed a reported $4 million before they were caught.
[src:backdraft/arson] Fire may be set for emotional satisfaction, firefighter arson, personal entertainment, or as a tool of assault or revenge.
[src:backdraft/arson] Arson investigator John Leonard Orr and other firefighter arsonists have been convicted of setting fires either personal entertainment or as a form of hero syndrome.
[src:backdraft/arson] Arsonists may set a fire in an attempt to damage a small amount of property (as revenge against a landlord, employer, friend or relative) without understanding how quickly a fire can spread.
[src:backdraft/arson] The Dupont Plaza Hotel which killed 99 persons happened after three striking workers set fire to a storeroom of new furniture.
[src:backdraft/arson] The fire flashed over and ignited the ballroom and shortly, the rest of the hotel.
[src:backdraft/arson] Artist Lisa Lopes accidentally burned down the mansion she shared with Andre Rison in 1994 after setting fire to his sneakers in a bathtub.
[src:backdraft/arson] Many deadly fires have been set during or following arguments.
[src:backdraft/arson] A person may also commit arson as the result of a psychotic episode as a result of delusions or hallucinations and may or may not be found criminally insane.
[src:backdraft/arson] Some arsonists have been committed to psychiatric hospitals instead of prison.
[src:backdraft/arson] Additional reasons for arson include an attempt to conceal another crime like robbery or homicide.
[src:backdraft/arson] These attempts are often unsuccessful at hiding blunt trauma, stab wounds, and gunshot wounds.
[src:backdraft/arson] Medical examiners may use a blood test and/or look for soot in the esophagus, lungs or mouth to check if the decedent was alive at the time of a fire.
[src:backdraft/arson] Arson exists in a variety of legal definitions worldwide.
[src:backdraft/arson] In many counties, including the Commonwealth, France, "arson" generally refers to a subsection of criminal or property damage.
[src:backdraft/arson] Generally, offenses are more severe when human lives were endangered.
[src:backdraft/arson] Some countries like Scotland differentiate the act of arson into wilful fire raising (the damage to property) and culpable and reckless conduct (injury to a person).
[src:backdraft/arson] English common law defines arson as "the malicious burning of the dwelling of another".
[src:backdraft/arson] For purposes of common law arson, "malicious" refers to intention of starting the fire.
[src:backdraft/arson] Fires can be started on purpose or by accident.
[src:backdraft/arson] to charge the guilty person with arson whether their intention was to start a fire or not.
[src:backdraft/arson] "Malicious" in this case describes the intention of the arsonist as ill-intentioned and intending to cause harm or death.
[src:backdraft/arson] According to common law, charring to any part of a dwelling is sufficient to satisfy this element.
[src:backdraft/arson] No significant amount of damage to the dwelling is required.
[src:backdraft/arson] Any injury or damage to the structure caused by exposure to heat or flame is sufficient.
[src:backdraft/arson] 'Dwelling' refers to a place of residence.
[src:backdraft/arson] At common law, a structure does not become a residence until the first occupants has moved in, and ceases to be a dwelling if the occupants abandon the premises with no intention of resuming their residency.
[src:backdraft/arson] 'Dwelling' includes structures and outbuildings within the curtilage.
[src:backdraft/arson] A barn can be the subject of arson if occupied as a dwelling.
[src:backdraft/arson] Burning one's own dwelling does not constitute common law arson, even if the purpose were to collect insurance, because "it was generally assumed in early England that one had the legal right to destroy his own property in any manner he chose".
[src:backdraft/arson] Moreover, for purposes of common law arson, possession or occupancy rather than title determines whose dwelling the structure is.
[src:backdraft/arson] while the landlord who set fire to a rented dwelling house he owned would be guilty.
[src:backdraft/arson] In the United States, the common law elements of arson are often varied in different jurisdictions.
[src:backdraft/arson] For example, the element of "dwelling" is no longer required in most states, and arson occurs by the burning of any real property without consent or with unlawful intent.
[src:backdraft/arson] Arson is prosecuted with attention to degree of severity in the alleged offense, but some states do not categorize arson by any degree.
[src:backdraft/arson] In the state of Tennessee, arson is categorized as "arson" and "aggravated arson".
[src:backdraft/arson] First degree arson generally occurs when people are harmed or killed in the course of the fire, while second degree arson occurs when significant destruction of property occurs.
[src:backdraft/arson] While usually a felony, arson may also be prosecuted as a misdemeanor, "criminal mischief", or "destruction of property".
[src:backdraft/arson] Burglary also occurs, if the arson involved a "breaking and entering".
[src:backdraft/arson] In states with the death penalty and in federal law, a person may be sentenced to death if arson occurred as a method of homicide, as was the case in California of Raymond Lee Oyler and in Texas of Cameron Todd Willingham.
[src:backdraft/arson] In several U.S. state legal systems (and nations like France) arson is divided into degrees depending the value of the property.
[src:backdraft/arson] It may also include additional penalties if the crime was committed during the day or night.
[src:backdraft/arson] Many statutes vary the degree of the crime according to the criminal intent of the accused.
[src:backdraft/arson] Some US states use other degrees of arson, such as "fourth" and "fifth" degree.
[src:backdraft/arson] In New York, arson is charged in five degrees.
[src:backdraft/arson] Arson in the first degree is a Class A-1 felony and requires the intent to burn the building with a person inside using an explosive incendiary device.
[src:backdraft/arson] In New York, the criminal charge of arson includes a maximum sentence of 25 years to life.
[src:backdraft/arson] In California, a conviction for arson of property that is not one's own is a felony punishable by up to three years in state prison.
[src:backdraft/arson] Aggravated arson, which carries the most severe punishment for arson, is punishable by 10 years to life in state prison.
[src:backdraft/arson] A well-known example of arson which took place in California is the Esperanza Fire.
[src:backdraft/arson] Raymond Lee Oyler was ultimately convicted of murder and sentenced to death for a 2006 fire in southern California that led to the deaths of five U.S.
[src:backdraft/arson] Forest Service firefighters; he was the first U.S. citizen to receive such a conviction and penalty for wildfire arson.
[src:backdraft/arson] Some states, such as California, prosecute the lesser offense of reckless burning when the fire is set recklessly as opposed to willfully and maliciously.
[src:backdraft/arson] The study of the causes is the subject of fire investigation.
[src:backdraft/arson] A recent example of a reckless burning offense is the El Dorado fire which took place in 2020 in California.
[src:backdraft/arson] This fire was caused by a gender reveal party which utilized a smoke bomb which is categorized as unsafe pyrotechnics.
[src:backdraft/arson] The El Dorado fire burned over a 71-day period, destroyed 20 structures and resulted in one firefighter fatality, for which the couple hosting the party were charged with involuntary manslaughter.
[src:backdraft/arson] The El Dorado Fire ultimately resulted in the death of firefighter Charles "Charlie" Morton, who became trapped while attempting to fight the fire.
[src:backdraft/arson] The DA of California considered arson charges for the family members as they were deemed negligent with regard to fire safety.
[src:backdraft/arson] During World War II, arson was a much higher concern in the United States.
[src:backdraft/arson] There was a severe lack of firefighters due to World War Two.
[src:backdraft/arson] There were few men left behind to help combat forest fires.
[src:backdraft/arson] For example, in Eldora, Iowa, a fire chief reported that his regular membership shrank from 21 to 9 men and their fire fighting force recruited retired members and new members to fill the missing positions during the war.
[src:backdraft/arson] There were additional concerns about wildfires on the west coast, especially following the 1942 Fu-Go balloon bomb incidents.
[src:backdraft/arson] Rather than report on the incendiary bombs, the Office of Censorship instead focuses efforts on "reducing forest fires".
[src:backdraft/arson] On April 7, 2026, in Ontario, California, a warehouse employee was arrested on suspicion of arson after a large fire broke out in a Kimberly-Clark paper-goods warehouse.
[src:backdraft/arson] The suspect reportedly filmed the incident and uploaded the footage to social media while saying "If you're not going to pay us enough to fucking live or afford to live, at least pay us enough not to do this".
[src:backdraft/arson] Three days later, on April 10, a second suspect was arrested on charges of arson after setting several small fires at the Ontario Mills mall.
[src:backdraft/arson] It is unknown if the two incidents were related.
[src:backdraft/arson] In English law, arson was a common law offence until 1971 (except for the offence of arson in royal dockyards, which is statutory).
[src:backdraft/arson] The common law offence was abolished by section 11 (1) of the Criminal Damage Act 1971.
[src:backdraft/arson] Section 1 (3) defines arson as criminal damage committed by fire; in contrast to common law arson, the property damaged or destroyed need not be a dwelling.
[src:backdraft/arson] Section 4 of the Act provides a maximum penalty of life imprisonment for conviction on indictment.
[src:backdraft/arson] A variety of notable arsons have occurred in England.
[src:backdraft/arson] In 1680 Margaret Clark and her accomplice John Satterthwayt burned down her employer's home.
[src:backdraft/arson] Clark blamed her actions on pride and breaking the sabbath.
[src:backdraft/arson] In 1791 in Birmingham, the Priestley Riots destroyed several buildings.
[src:backdraft/arson] Between 1912 and 1914 women's suffragists like Emmeline Pankhurst, Emily Davison, and other women in Great Britain and Ireland launched a campaign of arson and bombings to obtain the vote for women.
[src:backdraft/arson] Peter Dinsdale, AKA Bruce George Peter Lee, confessed to a total of 11 acts of arson, pleading guilty to 26 counts of manslaughter.
[src:backdraft/arson] Michelle Confait was murdered in London in 1972 and her house was set alight.
[src:backdraft/arson] In 2008, two students were found murdered in a flat in New Cross.
[src:backdraft/arson] The killer set the flat on fire to hide evidence.
[src:backdraft/arson] In 1981 thirteen teenagers died as the result of a fire started at a house party in New Cross, the cause of which has been speculated to be arson (both investigations returned an open verdict).
[src:backdraft/arson] In Hong Kong, the common law offence was abolished by s.
[src:backdraft/arson] 67 of the Crimes Ordinance 1971 (Part VIII of which, as amended by the Crimes (Amendment) Ordinance 1972, mirrored the English Criminal Damage Act 1971).
[src:backdraft/arson] Like the English counterparts, section 63 of the 1972 Ordinance provides a maximum penalty of life imprisonment, and s.
[src:backdraft/arson] 60(3) of the Ordinance requires that if the damage is by fire the offence should be charged as arson.
[src:backdraft/arson] A Molotov cocktail damaged a metro station during the 2019–2020 Hong Kong protests.
[src:backdraft/arson] Fire bombs, molotov cocktails and other incendiary devices were commonly used by militants during The Troubles.
[src:backdraft/arson] In 2025 several buildings were destroyed along with motorbikes and vehicles in a riot following a sexual assault.
[src:backdraft/arson] In the Burmese legal system, arson is considered "mischief by fire" under sections 435 and 436 of the Myanmar Penal Code and punishable by fine and imprisonment.
[src:backdraft/arson] The statutes were last amended on 1 July 2016, and made arson on houses and buildings punishable with up to 20 years in prison.
[src:backdraft/arson] A number of buildings were set on fire during the U Thant funeral crisis in 1974.
[src:backdraft/arson] In 2013 a series of riots resulted in a number of arson related deaths after anti-Muslim riots.
[src:backdraft/arson] The Burmese military has long used arson as a weapon of war against civilians.
[src:backdraft/arson] Between the 2021 Myanmar coup d'état and August 2022, military forces committed arson on 28,434 houses in the country.
[src:backdraft/arson] While the Scottish legal system has no offence known as arson statutorily defined, there are many offences that are used to charge those with acts that would normally constitute arson in other nations.
[src:backdraft/arson] Events constituting arson in English and Welsh law might be dealt with as one or more of a variety of offences such as wilful fire-raising, culpable and reckless conduct, vandalism or other offences depending on the circumstances of the event.
[src:backdraft/arson] The more serious offences (in particular wilful fire-raising and culpable and reckless conduct) can incur a sentence of life imprisonment.
[src:backdraft/arson] In 2023, three young boys were charged in connection with the Ayr Station Hotel fire.
[src:backdraft/arson] In Kilmarnock, two boys were arrested after accidentally burning down several buildings.
[src:backdraft/arson] Ireland differentiates how it charges arson not by degree but rather by what is being destroyed and if anyone was harmed.
[src:backdraft/arson] For example, while the sentence for setting fire to a building can be life imprisonment, the sentence for setting fire to goods in a building can only be up to fourteen years.
[src:backdraft/arson] A notable historical act of arson in Ireland is the burning of Wildgoose Lodge, which resulted in the arrest, sentencing, and execution of 18 men, many of whom were innocent.
[src:backdraft/arson] More recently, the 2023 Dublin riot involved instances of arson, with many such acts targeting vehicles.
[src:backdraft/arson] Murrough O'Brien, 1st Earl of Inchiquin, an Irish nobleman and soldier, was known as *Murchadh na dTóiteán* ("Murrough the Burner") for his role in the Sack of Cashel and other similar atrocities during the Cromwellian conquest of Ireland.
[src:backdraft/arson] In the Philippines, arson, alongside almost all illegal acts is governed by the Revised Penal Code (RPC).
[src:backdraft/arson] 1613, arson is generally divided into two categories: Simple Arson and Destructive Arson.
[src:backdraft/arson] Simple Arson constitutes intentional burning of property that excludes any serious and aggravating circumstances that would elevate the crime to destructive arson.
[src:backdraft/arson] Examples are the burning of houses, cars, vehicles, crops, etc.
[src:backdraft/arson] On the other hand, Destructive Arson is a more severe form of arson, characterized by extensive damages to the property and poses a direct threat to public safety.
[src:backdraft/arson] Examples include structures that maybe inhabited or occupied, buildings intended for public use, the intentional burning of a property that poses a direct threat to life and the burning of industrial establishments or facilities.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] A **backdraft** (North American English), **backdraught** (British English) or **smoke explosion** is the abrupt burning of superheated gases in a fire caused when oxygen rapidly enters a hot, oxygen-depleted environment; for example, when a window or door to an enclosed space is opened or broken.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] Backdrafts are typically seen as a blast of smoke and/or flame out of an opening of a building.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] Backdrafts present a serious threat to firefighters.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] There is some debate concerning whether backdrafts should be considered a type of flashover.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] When material is heated enough, it begins to break down into smaller compounds, including flammable or even explosive gas, typically hydrocarbons.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] This is called pyrolysis, and does not require oxygen.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] If oxygen is also provided, then the hydrocarbons can combust, starting a fire.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] If material undergoing pyrolysis is later given sufficient oxygen, the hydrocarbons will ignite and, therefore, combustion takes place.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] A backdraft can occur when a compartment fire has little or no ventilation.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] Due to this, little or no oxygen can flow into the compartment.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] Then, because fires reduce oxygen, the oxygen concentration decreases.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] When the oxygen concentration becomes too low to support combustion, some or all of the combustion switches to pyrolysis.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] Nonetheless, the hydrocarbons and smoke (primarily particulate matter) remain at a temperature hot enough to auto-ignite.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] The colour and movement of smoke is used by firefighters to infer fire conditions, including the risk of backdraft.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] This is an indication that the room lacks enough oxygen to permit oxidation of the soot particles.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] Firefighters often look to see if there is soot on the inside of windows and in any cracks in the window (caused e.g. by the heat).
[src:backdraft/backdraft] The windows may also have a slight vibration due to varying pressure within the compartment due to intermittent combustion.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] If firefighters discover a room sucking air into itself, for example through a crack, they generally evacuate immediately, because this is a strong indication that a backdraft is imminent.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] Due to pressure differences, puffs of smoke are sometimes drawn back into the enclosed space from which they emanated, which is how the term *backdraft* originated.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] Backdrafts are very dangerous, often surprising even experienced firefighters.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] The most common tactic used by firefighters to defuse a potential backdraft is to ventilate a room from its highest point, allowing the heat and smoke to escape without igniting.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] In common usage, the term flashover describes the near-simultaneous ignition of material caused by heat attaining the autoignition temperature of the combustible material and gases in an enclosure.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] Flashovers according to this narrower definition, i.e. those caused by rising temperatures, would not be considered backdrafts since backdrafts are caused by the introduction of oxygen into an enclosed space with conditions already suitable for ignition, and are thus caused by chemical change.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] Backdrafts were publicized by the 1991 movie *Backdraft*, in which a serial arsonist in Chicago uses them as a means of assassinating conspirators in a scam.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] In the film adaptation of Stephen King's *1408*, the protagonist Mike Enslin induces one as a last-ditch effort to kill the room.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] The term is also used and is the title of a scene in the 2012 video game *Root Double: Before Crime * After Days*.
[src:backdraft/backdraft] In the second book of the light novel series Imperial Reincarnation: I Came, I Saw, I Survived, the character Carmine uses a magically produced backdraft to defend himself against an assassination attempt.
